sections.english:
“Monks, this night, a certain deity, when the night was far advanced, of surpassing beauty, illuminating the entire Jeta’s Grove, approached me; having approached, she paid homage to me and stood to one side. Monks, as she stood to one side, that deity spoke to me thus – ‘Venerable sir, these seven qualities conduce to a monk’s non-decline. Which seven? Reverence for the Teacher, reverence for the Dhamma, reverence for the Saṅgha, reverence for the training, reverence for concentration, reverence for moral shame, and reverence for moral dread. Indeed, Venerable sir, these seven qualities conduce to a monk’s non-decline.’ Monks, that deity said this. Having said this, she paid homage to me, circumambulated me clockwise, and vanished right there.”

One who reveres the Teacher, reveres the Dhamma, and has intense reverence for the Saṅgha;
One who reveres concentration, is ardently diligent, and has intense reverence for the training.
Endowed with moral shame and moral dread, respectful and deferential;
Is incapable of decline; indeed, such a one is close to Nibbāna.

Monks, this night, a certain deity, having approached me and stood to one side, said this to me: ‘Venerable Sir, these seven qualities lead to a monk’s non-decline. Which seven? They are: profound reverence for the Teacher, profound reverence for the Dhamma, profound reverence for the Sangha, profound reverence for the training, profound reverence for concentration, amenability to instruction, and noble friendship. Venerable Sir, these seven qualities indeed lead to a monk’s non-decline.’ Monks, that deity said this. Having said this, having paid homage to me, having circumambulated me with their right side towards me, they vanished right there.

One who reveres the Teacher, reveres the Dhamma, and has intense reverence for the Sangha;
who reveres concentration, is ardent, and has intense reverence for the training;
who is a noble friend, amenable to instruction, respectful, and reverent—
such a one is incapable of decline and is indeed close to Nibbāna.
